{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"c5f33a6f-37bc-4d76-a938-86ddff7613ce","content":"In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle event mapping** in `MauiProgram.cs` (or your app's builder configuration):\n\n```csharp\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#elif IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\nAdd `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;` at the top.\n\nThis registers delegates that fire when the native platform raises those events, without requiring custom platform renderers or subclassing the `Activity`/`AppDelegate`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"491d0e85-c2f2-4c14-8534-cb8bb2332113","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI - specifically Android's OnPause/OnStop and iOS's DidEnterBackground. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development that I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":280,"requestId":"E84D:203FDB:263EF63:2A47DCD:69F93EF8"},"id":"64382209-0841-40ca-ac7f-16bb33de88e8","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:51:11.706Z","parentId":"6d9dd818-37ac-448c-a9bb-1bf33e118260"}
